	<h2 class="headerColor">What Am I Supposed To Be Concerned About?</h2>
				
	<p>You should be concerned that what you <b>value</b> about the Oregon coast is <b>vulnerable</b> to the <b>impacts of climate change and variability.</b></p>
				
	<p><i><b>How do I know what to value?</b></i> It is a good question that only you can answer. Value is defined as worth, desirability, or utility based on individual preferences. The total value of any resource is the sum of the values of the different individuals involved in the use of the resource (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change 2007). Start by thinking about things you know that you value about the Oregon coast. What you value could be based on a personal experience traveling to the coast, or it could be based on what you know about the economic livelihood of your entire community. Also, listen to what other people are saying.</p>
				
	<p><i><b>How do I know whether what I value will could be impacted by regional climate change and variability?</b></i>
	It is also a good question, but probably not something you can answer yourself without good scientific information.
	Look at the section below entitled "Nine Ways that Climate Change and Variability Could Impact What You Value." You might discover that the things you value 
    most are not likely to impacted by climate change and variability. 
	What you value more right now about the Oregon coast might change depending on what you learn about potential future impacts.</p>
				
	<p><i><b>How do I know whether what I value is vulnerable?</b></i> Ask yourself whether you are concerned about regional climate change and variability on the Oregon coast because it impacts what you value most, because it impacts what you think is most vulnerable, or a little of both. Then ask yourself where the vulnerability comes from? Are you concerned because it seems what you value is highly exposed to climate change and variability? Are you concerned because it seems what you value is highly sensitive to climate change and variability? Or are you concerned because you do not think that your public agency decision makers, the scientific experts, or others are doing enough to help you deal with the impacts of climate change and variability on what you value?</p>
				
	<p><i><b>By the way, am I supposed to know the difference between climate change and climate variability?</b></i>
	It probably wouldn't hurt. See below.</p>
				
	<h2 class="headerColor">Climate Change vs. Climate Variability</h2>
				
	<p>According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), climate <b>change</b> refers to a <b>statistically significant variation</b> in
	either the mean state of the climate or in its variability,
	persisting for an extended period (typically decades or longer).
	Climate change may be due to natural internal processes or
	external forcings, or to persistent anthropogenic changes in
	the composition of the atmosphere or in land use. Note that
	the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate
	Change (UNFCCC), in its Article 1, defines “climate change”
	as: “a change of climate which is attributed directly or
	indirectly to human activity that alters the composition of the
	global atmosphere and which is in addition to natural climate
	variability observed over comparable time periods.” The
	UNFCCC thus makes a distinction between “climate change”
	attributable to human activities altering the atmospheric
	composition, and “climate variability” attributable to natural
	causes.</p>
				
	<p>Climate <b>variability</b> refers to <b>variations</b> in the mean state and other
	statistics (such as standard deviations, the occurrence of extremes,
	etc.) of the climate on all temporal and spatial scales beyond
	that of individual weather events. Variability may be due to
	natural internal processes within the climate system (internal
	variability), or to variations in natural or anthropogenic
	external forcing (external variability).</p>
				
